<br>
However, we are a permanent member of the security council, along with china and russia, who both dont want north korea to have these weapons.<br>
<br>
we are just the mechanism for the UN to go after countries, so we take the blame for any UN operation gone awry.  Of course, we are the &quot;evil americans.&quot;<br>
<br>
It is very hard to say.  But I really dont see why we want instruments of such mass destruction at our disposal anyway.  Wars shouldnt exist.  In this day and age, except for the religious disputes in the middle east, wars shouldnt be on anyones mind.  Especially with our global economy, more so every day. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 726<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/17/03 9:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=351.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: N.Korea announces it is to resume missile tests.</span><hr size=1> If we didn't have nuclear weapons and the assurance of &quot;MAD&quot; there probably would have been much more bigger and bloodier wars in the 20th Century than otherwise happened.  I don't think people give the threat of nuclear retaliation enough credit for actually keeping the peace.  As a modern example, I'm willing to bet India and Pakistan would be viciously trying to kill each other right now if the threat of being nuked wasn't on their heads.   Considering the ecological damage and the human suffering that wars usually cause, people who hate nuclear power in any form might have to face up to the fact that if it weren't for nukes it's quite possible we'd be far worse off than we are now. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2926<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/18/03 4:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=351.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: N.Korea announces it is to resume missile tests.</span><hr size=1> Very true. We are walking a tightrope between two 10 km high frictionless poles. One we might fall off from at any time but can only keep walking. We can't get off the rope as there is nowhere to go except down into oblivion. If we sever either ends of the rope which are marked &quot;Excessive Proliferation&quot; and &quot;Nuclear Free Zone&quot;, we die. We need a third option and as I've said many times before I think the only remaining choice is a bigger scarier stick than even the nuclear bogeyman which can be kept out of enemy hands.<br>
<br>
Wars will always exist. They are a part of our nature and we are no less savage than our ancestors were. Wars only give way to peace when the prospect of war becomes unbearable. Nuclear weapons have kept the peace for decades but it couldn't last. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tmayes1999>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 183<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/18/03 2:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=351.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: N.Korea announces it is to resume missile tests.</span><hr size=1> 1.Good governments should always  have nuclear weapons.<br>
